Fletcher, 1958
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2E5A36DBAD23FFFFFF73A967B095150C" blockId="4.[151,1436,613,1070]" pageId="4" pageNumber="229">
<emphasis id="1C91EAC9AD23FFFFFF73A967B36B135C" bold="true" box="[151,352,613,638]" pageId="4" pageNumber="229">Taxonomic notes</emphasis>
. The genus 
<taxonomicName id="E9E54D58AD23FFFFFE08A967B0BD135C" authority="Leach, 1815" authorityName="Leach" authorityYear="1815" box="[492,694,613,638]" class="Insecta" family="Nolidae" genus="Nola" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="229" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="1C91EAC9AD23FFFFFE08A967B028135C" box="[492,547,613,638]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="229">Nola</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="4A744B2AAD23FFFFFDCFA967B0BD135C" author="Leach E. E." box="[555,694,613,638]" pageId="4" pageNumber="229" pagination="135" refId="ref14012" refString="Leach E. E. (1815) The Zoological Miscellany; being descriptions of new, or interesting animals. New Edinburg Encyclopedia 9, 135." type="journal article" year="1815">Leach, 1815</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
has several hundreds of species distributed worldwide. The most important diagnostic characters of the genus is the deeply cleft bilobate valva, and the lacking of uncus, while the also species rich African taxon 
<taxonomicName id="E9E54D58AD23FFFFFE13A9AFB10C13E4" authority="Hacker, 2012" authorityName="Hacker" authorityYear="2012" box="[503,775,685,710]" class="Insecta" family="Nolidae" genus="Nola" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="229" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Mecothrix">
<emphasis id="1C91EAC9AD23FFFFFE13A9AFB06013E4" box="[503,619,685,710]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="229">Mecothrix</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="4A744B2AAD23FFFFFD95A9AFB10C13E4" author="Hacker, H. H. &amp; Schreier, H. P. &amp; Goater, B." box="[625,775,685,710]" pageId="4" pageNumber="229" pagination="7 - 612" refId="ref13560" refString="Hacker, H. H., Schreier, H. P. &amp; Goater, B. (2012) Revision of the tribe Nolini of Africa and the Western Palaearctic Region (Lepidoptera, Noctuoidea, Noctuidae, Nolinae). Esperiana, 17, 7 - 612." type="journal article" year="2012">Hacker, 2012</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
has completely different valval structure (broad, uncleft or just slightly concave apically, weakly sclerotized with membraneous costal margin), a special feature of the pair of dense, extraordinarily long, easily removeable androconial hair-tufts arising from a pocket-like lateral extension of vinculum, in addition the very unique single, large, needle- or robust thorn-like cornutus of the vesica. In the female genitalia morphology, species of the genus 
<taxonomicName id="E9E54D58AD23FFFFFD29A83FB1081274" authorityName="Leach" authorityYear="1815" box="[717,771,829,854]" class="Insecta" family="Nolidae" genus="Nola" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="229" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="1C91EAC9AD23FFFFFD29A83FB1081274" box="[717,771,829,854]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="229">Nola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
display quite large diversity but in general have longer and predominantly membraneous ductus bursae only with shorter sections of heavier sclerotization or dilation, whereas the females of 
<taxonomicName id="E9E54D58AD23FFFFFEAFA887B3B412BC" authorityName="Hacker" authorityYear="2012" box="[331,447,901,926]" class="Insecta" family="Nolidae" genus="Nola" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="229" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Mecothrix">
<emphasis id="1C91EAC9AD23FFFFFEAFA887B3B412BC" box="[331,447,901,926]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="229">Mecothrix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have significantly stronger and, in most cases much longer sclerotization of ductus bursae, in addition the pair of elongate, finger-, or claw-like signum bursae of 
<taxonomicName id="E9E54D58AD23FFFFFB8FA8ABB6D512E0" authorityName="Hacker" authorityYear="2012" box="[1131,1246,937,962]" class="Insecta" family="Nolidae" genus="Nola" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="229" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Mecothrix">
<emphasis id="1C91EAC9AD23FFFFFB8FA8ABB6D512E0" box="[1131,1246,937,962]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="229">Mecothrix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species is also characteristic for the genus. As the extent of the differences in the ground plan of the genital morphology between 
<taxonomicName id="E9E54D58AD23FFFFFF73A8F3B3691528" authority="Leach, 1815" authorityName="Leach" authorityYear="1815" box="[151,354,1009,1034]" class="Insecta" family="Nolidae" genus="Nola" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="229" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="1C91EAC9AD23FFFFFF73A8F3B2C51528" box="[151,206,1009,1034]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="229">Nola</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="4A744B2AAD23FFFFFF32A8F3B3691528" author="Leach E. E." box="[214,354,1009,1034]" pageId="4" pageNumber="229" pagination="135" refId="ref14012" refString="Leach E. E. (1815) The Zoological Miscellany; being descriptions of new, or interesting animals. New Edinburg Encyclopedia 9, 135." type="journal article" year="1815">Leach, 1815</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and the recently established subgenus 
<taxonomicName id="E9E54D58AD23FFFFFCFAA8F3B63A1528" authority="Hacker, 2012" authorityName="Hacker" authorityYear="2012" box="[798,1073,1009,1034]" class="Insecta" family="Nolidae" genus="Nola" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="229" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Mecothrix">
<emphasis id="1C91EAC9AD23FFFFFCFAA8F3B19A1528" box="[798,913,1009,1034]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="229">Mecothrix</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="4A744B2AAD23FFFFFC7DA8F3B63A1528" author="Hacker, H. H. &amp; Schreier, H. P. &amp; Goater, B." box="[921,1073,1009,1034]" pageId="4" pageNumber="229" pagination="7 - 612" refId="ref13560" refString="Hacker, H. H., Schreier, H. P. &amp; Goater, B. (2012) Revision of the tribe Nolini of Africa and the Western Palaearctic Region (Lepidoptera, Noctuoidea, Noctuidae, Nolinae). Esperiana, 17, 7 - 612." type="journal article" year="2012">Hacker, 2012</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
is so substantial, distinguishing 
<taxonomicName id="E9E54D58AD23FFFFFF73AF17B301150C" authorityName="Hacker" authorityYear="2012" box="[151,266,1045,1070]" class="Insecta" family="Nolidae" genus="Nola" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="229" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Mecothrix">
<emphasis id="1C91EAC9AD23FFFFFF73AF17B301150C" box="[151,266,1045,1070]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="229">Mecothrix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a distinct genus is fully justified.
</paragraph>
